Oh! My goodness.
Of course. Here. take mine.

5
00:01:06.588 --> 00:01:08.720
I appreciate that
both of you are here.

6
00:01:10.070 --> 00:01:12.072
What happened?

7
00:01:12.115 --> 00:01:14.378
The children were at the water
fountain during gym

8
00:01:14.422 --> 00:01:15.901
and Sally told Becky Pierson

9
00:01:15.945 --> 00:01:18.295
she should save some for the
fish.

10
00:01:18.339 --> 00:01:20.993
and Becky ignored her.

11
00:01:21.037 --> 00:01:24.258
and Sally hit the back of her head
and her face went into the spigot.

12
00:01:24.301 --> 00:01:26.521
And then Becky went after her...

13
00:01:26.564 --> 00:01:28.566
Hair pulling. scratching.

14
00:01:31.439 --> 00:01:33.484
She didn't need stitches in the end.
I understand?

15
00:01:33.528 --> 00:01:36.792
This girl. this Becky Pierson.

16
00:01:36.835 --> 00:01:38.489
Sally told me she's a bruiser.

17
00:01:38.533 --> 00:01:39.795
She's heavy.

18
00:01:41.840 --> 00:01:44.278
The children poke pencils
into her sides when she's sitting

19
00:01:44.321 --> 00:01:46.280
because they think she can't
feel it.

20
00:01:46.323 --> 00:01:47.759
Sally doesn't do that. does she?

21
00:01:48.108 --> 00:01:50.153
No.

22
00:01:50.197 --> 00:01:54.157
But this bad behavior is new.

23
00:01:54.201 --> 00:01:55.419
I know that you're expecting a
child.

24
00:01:55.463 --> 00:01:57.987
but she already has a little
brother.

25
00:01:58.030 --> 00:02:02.296
I guess what I'm asking is. has
anything changed at home recently?

26
00:02:04.907 --> 00:02:11.392
My. um... My father passed away. Last week.

27
00:02:15.135 --> 00:02:17.311
The week before... Two weeks
now.

28
00:02:21.184 --> 00:02:24.709
I feel terrible for bringing
that up for you.

29
00:02:24.753 --> 00:02:26.146
Well. it has not been easy.

30
00:02:30.411 --> 00:02:34.676
Is this Grandpa Gene we're talking about?
Oh. that poor thing.

31
00:02:35.416 --> 00:02:37.244
Sally didn't mention it?

32
00:02:37.287 --> 00:02:40.508
Why didn't you call
us or send a note?

33
00:02:41.813 --> 00:02:44.903
I don't think she missed a day.

34
00:02:44.947 --> 00:02:46.862
Did she go to the funeral?

35
00:02:46.905 --> 00:02:49.038
Why would we put her through
that?

36
00:02:49.081 --> 00:02:51.083
I don't think children
belong in graveyards.

37
00:02:54.217 --> 00:02:55.784
No. of course not.

38
00:02:57.220 --> 00:02:59.309
Now I realize why she was
asking all those questions

39
00:02:59.353 --> 00:03:01.224
about Medgar Evers' murder.

40
00:03:01.268 --> 00:03:02.225
She was?

41
00:03:03.226 --> 00:03:05.533
I'm sorry.

42
00:03:05.576 --> 00:03:07.883
I have to use the ladies room
again.

43
00:03:07.926 --> 00:03:09.667
We can talk about this another
time.

44
00:03:09.711 --> 00:03:12.322
No. I'm not as upset as I look.
I can't help this.

45
00:03:23.072 --> 00:03:24.465
I am mortified.

46
00:03:24.856 --> 00:03:26.467
It's not a good time.

47
00:03:26.510 --> 00:03:29.948
No. and it really should be.
shouldn't it?

48
00:03:31.167 --> 00:03:34.953
Sally does need more attention.
She's grieving.

49
00:03:36.520 --> 00:03:40.829
There is a very special pain
to losing someone at that age.

50
00:03:43.179 --> 00:03:45.573
I don't know if you
can understand that.

51
00:03:48.315 --> 00:03:49.316
I can.

52
00:03:57.149 --> 00:04:01.893
Mrs. Draper. I was just talking to
your husband and this really can wait.

53
00:04:02.372 --> 00:04:03.678
Are you sure?

54
00:04:05.549 --> 00:04:08.900
Because I just want
to put it behind us.

55
00:04:08.944 --> 00:04:11.381
I really just want everything to be
okay when the baby comes.

56
00:04:12.904 --> 00:04:15.080
It's going to be a beautiful
summer.

57
00:04:21.391 --> 00:04:23.915
"Tipped a barman: 75
cents."

58
00:04:23.959 --> 00:04:27.136
"Hat-check tip at bar: 50
cents."

59
00:04:27.179 --> 00:04:30.226
"Cab to restaurant: $1.12.
Tipped the cab driver: 38 cents."

60
00:04:30.270 --> 00:04:32.837
"Dinner at Hausner's: $19.44."

61
00:04:35.231 --> 00:04:38.669
It's better to have a bit of Don
Draper than no Don Draper at all.

62
00:04:38.713 --> 00:04:42.107
I'd like that in writing.

63
00:04:42.151 --> 00:04:45.546
It seems strange that the two of
you went on the same overnight trip

64
00:04:45.589 --> 00:04:49.724
and you put in for $70 and
he put in for $82.

65
00:04:49.767 --> 00:04:52.553
If I were lying. wouldn't I
have made it a round number?

66
00:04:52.596 --> 00:04:54.772
Not that Don's lying.

67
00:04:54.816 --> 00:04:56.252
I signed his receipts. didn't I?

68
00:04:58.080 --> 00:05:02.737
Which brings us to the undocumented
portion of my assessment.

69
00:05:02.780 --> 00:05:07.481
The amount of pencils.
pens. pads. paper and postage

70
00:05:07.524 --> 00:05:11.311
that are currently being consumed
suit a company four times our size.

71
00:05:15.402 --> 00:05:20.363
It has also been brought to my
attention that a credenza has disappeared.

72
00:05:20.407 --> 00:05:24.324
a theft that I believe
necessitates a conspiracy.

73
00:05:24.367 --> 00:05:27.196
People forget that Karl Marx was
the greatest economist who ever lived.

74
00:05:27.239 --> 00:05:30.286
and whatever you think of his
solution. the problem he posed

75
00:05:30.330 --> 00:05:32.941
was about the catastrophic
up-and-down of the marketplace.

76
00:05:32.984 --> 00:05:36.597
Tell the folks at Admiral that
Karl Marx says everything's okay.

77
00:05:36.640 --> 00:05:39.861
Boom and bust. Bull and bear. "I need
a TV." "I have a TV."

78
00:05:39.904 --> 00:05:42.254
Damn it. Paul. someone
helped Ken cherry-pick

79
00:05:42.298 --> 00:05:44.909
all of Burt's successful accounts
and I've been left with the dogs.

80
00:05:44.953 --> 00:05:46.563
Admiral is not a dog.

81
00:05:46.607 --> 00:05:49.044
Sales are flat. It's all
over their memos.

82
00:05:49.087 --> 00:05:54.615
And now I have to look them in the eye
with nothing. Except maybe new creative.

83
00:05:55.442 --> 00:05:57.182
Stop it.

84
00:05:57.226 --> 00:05:59.881
Mmm. now you're interested.

85
00:05:59.924 --> 00:06:03.406
There are some areas of growth. and I
mean literally. areas.

86
00:06:03.450 --> 00:06:09.804
Atlanta. Oakland. Chicago.
Detroit. Newark. DC.

87
00:06:09.847 --> 00:06:11.675
Great jazz cities.

88
00:06:11.719 --> 00:06:14.374
And I left out St.
Louis and Kansas City. also growing.

89
00:06:16.201 --> 00:06:17.246
What does that mean?

90
00:06:17.289 --> 00:06:19.422
Great jazz musicians?

91
00:06:19.466 --> 00:06:23.818
Seriously. is it possible that these
Admirals are being bought by Negroes?

92
00:06:23.861 --> 00:06:26.690
Lois caught her scarf putting
paper in the Xerox.

93
00:06:26.734 --> 00:06:28.953
Maybe when Joan leaves I can
finally get rid of her.

94
00:06:28.997 --> 00:06:30.825
Can you pretend like you're backing
the media department

95
00:06:30.868 --> 00:06:33.958
and tell me what this says to you?
Look at the cities.

96
00:06:34.002 --> 00:06:36.700
Is it possible that Negroes are
out-buying other people two-to-one?

97
00:06:36.744 --> 00:06:40.443
You could jump to that
conclusion. I suppose.

98
00:06:40.487 --> 00:06:44.229
Did you hear about
Lois? You got a winner there. Kinsey.

99
00:06:44.273 --> 00:06:45.405
Did you see it?

100
00:06:45.448 --> 00:06:46.536
I did.

101
00:06:48.277 --> 00:06:49.974
So what's everybody doing
tonight?

102
00:06:50.018 --> 00:06:52.455
Baby. Married. Kinsey?

103
00:06:52.499 --> 00:06:56.546
Do you want to go to the Mets game?
Tickets and a watch.

104
00:06:56.590 --> 00:06:58.156
Why. thank you. Birds Eye.

105
00:06:58.200 --> 00:07:00.942
Does the watch say "Birds Eye"
on it?

106
00:07:00.985 --> 00:07:04.032
No. it says. "Hamilton
Electric."

107
00:07:04.075 --> 00:07:06.861
What time is it? What time isn't it?

108
00:07:09.124 --> 00:07:10.952
Admiral is happy. We're happy.

109
00:07:10.995 --> 00:07:13.084
They're not happy!

110
00:07:13.128 --> 00:07:17.219
"Morris. comma. in reference
to retooling the factory"

111
00:07:17.262 --> 00:07:19.308
"for London Fog children's
and young adults..."

112
00:07:22.529 --> 00:07:25.532
I thought I'd bring you the minutes to
the meeting. since you had to run off.

113
00:07:32.843 --> 00:07:34.671
You're wasting paper.

114
00:07:34.715 --> 00:07:37.457
I'd have to make 1.000 to
keep up with your department.

115
00:07:39.459 --> 00:07:41.939
They waste paper because they
throw out bad ideas.

116
00:07:41.983 --> 00:07:45.552
They waste paper because
they use it to sop up spilled drinks.

117
00:07:45.595 --> 00:07:47.510
right after their mid-afternoon
naps.

118
00:07:47.554 --> 00:07:49.643
You came here because we do
this better than you.

119
00:07:49.686 --> 00:07:52.994
and part of that is letting our
creatives be unproductive until they are.

120
00:07:53.037 --> 00:07:56.214
Pennies make pounds and
pounds make profits.

121
00:07:56.258 --> 00:07:59.653
I don't want to talk
to you this way.

122
00:07:59.696 --> 00:08:01.785
I've tried it before
and it never works.

123
00:08:02.656 --> 00:08:05.485
You're not usually this
emotional.

124
00:08:05.528 --> 00:08:06.486
You want to make money?

125
00:08:10.011 --> 00:08:11.229
Start getting your nails dirty

126
00:08:11.273 --> 00:08:14.755
with Bert Cooper and Harry
Crane.

127
00:08:14.798 --> 00:08:19.237
Clients love to pay for media
and creative needs pencils.

128
00:08:19.281 --> 00:08:21.283
I suppose I hadn't necessarily
thought of it that way.

129
00:08:21.326 --> 00:08:23.807
And lay off of expense accounts.

130
00:08:23.851 --> 00:08:27.158
Think of the men's morale.
not just your own.

131
00:08:27.202 --> 00:08:30.031
You've obviously seen Bridge
on the River Kwai.

132
00:08:30.074 --> 00:08:32.381
I've seen everything. You
have my ticket stubs.

133
00:08:32.424 --> 00:08:33.513
Hmm.

134
00:08:47.527 --> 00:08:50.834
Your uncle Herman is on
the line. He won't leave a message.

135
00:08:50.878 --> 00:08:54.925
Uncle Herman? My goodness. is
Aunt Alice all right?

136
00:08:54.969 --> 00:08:56.753
Who is this?

137
00:08:56.797 --> 00:08:59.234
It's Peter. Dottie's boy.
You called me.

138
00:08:59.277 --> 00:09:00.757
It's Duck. Duck Phillips.

139
00:09:01.323 --> 00:09:03.281
Duck.

140
00:09:03.325 --> 00:09:06.023
Sorry for the cloak and dagger.
I didn't want to set off any alarm bells.

141
00:09:06.067 --> 00:09:07.764
My name is Herman. you know
that.

142
00:09:09.113 --> 00:09:11.681
Except that I actually have an
Uncle Herman and he's 91.

143
00:09:11.725 --> 00:09:15.903
That's a sick joke.
I apologize. It's been too long.

144
00:09:15.946 --> 00:09:17.905
I don't know if you heard.
but I'm at Grey now.

145
00:09:18.427 --> 00:09:20.385
What's that like?

146
00:09:20.429 --> 00:09:23.301
People walking around the halls
all the time. laughing their heads off?

147
00:09:25.086 --> 00:09:26.740
We're going to have lunch. you
know.

148
00:09:26.783 --> 00:09:29.786
I don't know. Duck. It doesn't
sound like a good idea.

149
00:09:29.830 --> 00:09:32.354
Campbell. this is beyond
"No hard feelings."

150
00:09:32.397 --> 00:09:35.096
I won't waste your time. Haven't I
always been on your side?

151
00:09:38.534 --> 00:09:39.753
When?

152
00:09:39.796 --> 00:09:41.015
I'll have my girl call your
girl.

153
00:09:41.058 --> 00:09:42.494
I'll say it's Clorox.

154
00:09:51.373 --> 00:09:55.812
Hello? Anyone home?

155
00:09:58.206 --> 00:10:00.817
I'll get it. Hello?

156
00:10:00.861 --> 00:10:03.080
Mr. Draper? Yes.

157
00:10:03.124 --> 00:10:07.432
This is Suzanne Farrell.
Sally's teacher.

158
00:10:07.476 --> 00:10:09.391
I'm not interrupting dinner. am I?

159
00:10:10.392 --> 00:10:11.785
No.

160
00:10:11.828 --> 00:10:13.264
I just felt I should
call and apologize

161
00:10:13.308 --> 00:10:14.962
about our meeting this morning.

162
00:10:16.224 --> 00:10:17.225
Why?

163
00:10:21.403 --> 00:10:22.578
Well. I...

164
00:10:25.712 --> 00:10:30.630
What I mean is. my father
died when I was eight

165
00:10:30.673 --> 00:10:36.505
and I might have overdone it.
relating to Sally in that way.

166
00:10:36.548 --> 00:10:40.204
I didn't mean to upset your
wife. and...

167
00:10:40.248 --> 00:10:44.208
I guess I can get a little caught
up in things and lose perspective.

168
00:10:49.910 --> 00:10:53.217
I don't know why I'm calling.
I'm embarrassing myself.

169
00:10:53.261 --> 00:10:54.262
No. you're fine.

170
00:10:57.526 --> 00:10:59.006
If there's anything I can do...

171
00:10:59.049 --> 00:11:00.268
Don?

172
00:11:00.790 --> 00:11:02.009
Betts!

173
00:11:04.054 --> 00:11:05.795
Thanks for the call.

174
00:11:09.973 --> 00:11:12.193
It's time to go.

175
00:11:12.236 --> 00:11:14.108
Okay. we're going.
Let me get my keys.

176
00:11:14.630 --> 00:11:16.110
They're in your hand.

177
00:11:17.720 --> 00:11:20.723
Francine took the kids. Who was that?

178
00:11:21.550 --> 00:11:22.769
No one.

179
00:11:25.380 --> 00:11:28.078
If you're parked in emergency.
you'll have to move soon.

180
00:11:28.122 --> 00:11:30.472
First. let's make sure it's
not a false alarm.

181
00:11:30.515 --> 00:11:31.691
This is my third time.

182
00:11:31.734 --> 00:11:32.779
We sent you home before?

183
00:11:32.822 --> 00:11:33.997
No. third baby.

184
00:11:39.176 --> 00:11:41.701
Your job's done. The solarium's down
the hall to the right.

185
00:11:42.440 --> 00:11:44.181
Hang in there. Betts.

186
00:11:58.239 --> 00:11:59.849
I came in early to
cover for a friend.

187
00:11:59.893 --> 00:12:02.069
so there's a chance I'll see
you the whole way through.

188
00:12:05.899 --> 00:12:07.857
Daddy!

189
00:12:07.901 --> 00:12:10.033
You can scream and yell as much as
you want in this hallway.

190
00:12:10.077 --> 00:12:12.732
but we're about to pass the
nursery.

191
00:12:12.775 --> 00:12:13.733
Of course.

192
00:12:20.435 --> 00:12:22.437
Excuse me.

193
00:12:22.480 --> 00:12:25.092
I know it's silly. but I seem to be
having trouble with this pen.

194
00:12:25.135 --> 00:12:26.441
I believe it's empty.

195
00:12:26.484 --> 00:12:27.485
I gotta go.

196
00:12:31.272 --> 00:12:34.797
Are you planning
to give the baby the breast?

197
00:12:34.841 --> 00:12:36.320
No.

198
00:12:36.364 --> 00:12:37.365
Last time you ate?

199
00:12:39.323 --> 00:12:44.502
Lunch. Toast. cottage
cheese. pineapple.

200
00:12:44.546 --> 00:12:48.071
Pineapple? What were you thinking?
Anything else. sweetheart?

201
00:12:49.856 --> 00:12:52.162
Life Savers.

202
00:12:52.206 --> 00:12:53.947
Has your water broken?

203
00:12:53.990 --> 00:12:58.865
My water never breaks.
When will Dr. Aldridge be here?

204
00:13:04.740 --> 00:13:06.133
Joseph Waddell?

205
00:13:07.612 --> 00:13:09.658
I'm Dennis Hobart.

206
00:13:09.701 --> 00:13:11.703
That's good to know.

207
00:13:11.747 --> 00:13:15.055
I haven't seen anybody in an hour.
What's going on?

208
00:13:15.098 --> 00:13:16.273
Well. we've had a shift change.

209
00:13:16.317 --> 00:13:19.799
My wife. Pam. Pamela Hobart.

210
00:13:19.842 --> 00:13:21.452
She's fine. The baby's breech.

211
00:13:21.496 --> 00:13:23.063
We're calling in a specialist.

212
00:13:23.106 --> 00:13:24.760
What?

213
00:13:24.804 --> 00:13:26.457
Didn't somebody get your
permission?

214
00:13:26.501 --> 00:13:28.895
Damn it. what is with you people?
I don't know a damn thing!

215
00:13:28.938 --> 00:13:31.027
Please don't raise your voice.

216
00:13:31.071 --> 00:13:33.987
Now. I apologize. but we
need your permission.

217
00:13:34.030 --> 00:13:35.815
Do whatever you have to do.

218
00:13:35.858 --> 00:13:37.991
We'll update you religiously.
Promise.

219
00:13:47.914 --> 00:13:50.655
This is not how I pictured it.

220
00:13:50.699 --> 00:13:53.658
Where's all the backslapping?

221
00:13:53.702 --> 00:13:58.011
You know. I brought this because
I thought it'd be a party in here.

222
00:13:59.490 --> 00:14:00.883
It's not. but I'll have one.

223
00:14:00.927 --> 00:14:01.971
Right now?

224
00:14:02.015 --> 00:14:03.625
Whenever you want.

225
00:14:10.414 --> 00:14:13.374
I left work this morning. I've
been here all day.

226
00:14:14.636 --> 00:14:15.985
I am so bored.

227
00:14:19.554 --> 00:14:24.211
I even called in.
Like the prison can't run without me.

228
00:14:37.224 --> 00:14:38.268
You done this before?

229
00:14:39.922 --> 00:14:41.010
Twice.

230
00:14:42.969 --> 00:14:44.361
And yet I never thought to
bring a bottle.

231
00:14:45.493 --> 00:14:47.582
Well. what are we supposed to
do?

232
00:14:51.716 --> 00:14:56.330
My daughter took forever.
I remember being pretty worked up.

233
00:14:57.897 --> 00:15:00.290
And the nurse said. "Don't
forget."

234
00:15:00.334 --> 00:15:03.206
"Your wife's in the boat.
You're on the shore."

235
00:15:05.295 --> 00:15:08.081
The other one a boy?

236
00:15:08.124 --> 00:15:09.212
Yes.

237
00:15:12.041 --> 00:15:13.347
You throw the ball around?

238
00:15:16.045 --> 00:15:17.307
Not enough.

239
00:15:36.718 --> 00:15:38.720
All right. Mrs.
Draper.

240
00:15:38.763 --> 00:15:40.417
I'm going to need
you to get on the bed

241
00:15:40.461 --> 00:15:42.463
so I can prepare you for
delivery.

242
00:15:42.506 --> 00:15:44.204
This part should be familiar.

243
00:15:44.247 --> 00:15:47.337
I'll shave you and then
give you a quick low enema.

244
00:15:59.306 --> 00:16:01.351
Well. the good news
is. time has stopped.

245
00:16:02.962 --> 00:16:06.313
I'd like to have a gold watch
one day. but I can't. you know?

246
00:16:06.356 --> 00:16:08.184
You don't want to have
anything on you like that.

